Context for supporting a value of `None` for `lifetime_actions` is described in https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-python/pull/24059. After looking over Managed HSM responses and discussing with Laurent, we decided that using an empty list instead of `None` makes the most sense for `KeyRotationPolicy.lifetime_actions`, since the assumption in the regular case is that this attribute is iterable, even if empty. Other attributes have had their type hints updated, since we can't rely on the values we _expect_ to get back from Key Vault.

Other attributes have had their type hints updated, since we can't rely on the values we _expect_ to get back from Key Vault.

After looking over Managed HSM responses and discussing with Laurent, we decided that using an empty list instead of `None` makes the most sense for `KeyRotationPolicy.lifetime_actions`, since the assumption in the regular case is that this attribute is iterable, even if empty. Other attributes have had their type hints updated, since we can't rely on the values we _expect_ to get back from Key Vault.

'2022-04-07T22:55:42Z', 'closed_at': '2022-04-07T22:55:42Z', 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '```Python
from enum import Enum
from six import with_metaclass
from azure.core import CaseInsensitiveEnumMeta

class Answers(with_metaclass(CaseInsensitiveEnumMeta, str, Enum)):
    NONE = "none"
    EXTRACTIVE = "extractive"
```

If you try and run pylint on this, it will crash with an error that "Const is not iterable". (See: https://github.com/PyCQA/pylint/issues/5935)

Even if pylint fixes the error, we are pinned to pylint 2.5.2 and this still happens there.

This does not affect our SDKs much because most of these enums live in the `_generated` folder, which is skipped by our pylint `rcfile`. However, if someone follows our generated code and creates a manual enum, they will observe this behavior. Since we no longer support Python 2, we should start generating these enums with the Python 3 syntax, which is pylint-compatible:

```Python
from enum import Enum
from azure.core import CaseInsensitiveEnumMeta

class Answers(str, Enum, metaclass=CaseInsensitiveEnumMeta):
    NONE = "none"
    EXTRACTIVE = "extractive"
```

Thorough review of your client library ensures that your APIs are consistent with the guidelines and the consumers of your client library have a consistently good experience when using Azure. 

**The Architecture Board reviews [Track 2 libraries](https://azure.github.io/azure-sdk/general_introduction.html) only.** If your library does not meet this requirement, please reach out to [Architecture Board](adparch@microsoft.com) before creating the issue. 

Please reference our [review process guidelines](https://azure.github.io/azure-sdk/policies_reviewprocess.html) to understand what is being asked for in the issue template.

To ensure consistency, all Tier-1 languages (C#, TypeScript, Java, Python) will generally be reviewed together.  In expansive libraries, we will pair dynamic languages (Python, TypeScript) together, and strongly typed languages (C#, Java) together in separate meetings.

For Tier-2 languages (C, C++, Go, Android, iOS), the review will be on an as-needed basis.

**Before submitting, ensure you adjust the title of the issue appropriately.**

**Note that the required material must be included before a meeting can be scheduled.** 



## Contacts and Timeline

* Responsible service team:
* Main contacts: @lmazuel @johanste @iscai-msft @msyyc @changlong-liu 
* Review Date Requirements: Can we meet earliest second week of May? We also need for the meeting to be 4-6 pm to accommodate our developers in China

## About the Service 

* Link to documentation introducing/describing the service:
* Link to the service REST APIs: 
* Link to GitHub issue for previous review sessions, if applicable:  


## About the client library

* Name of the client library: 
* Languages for this review:

## Step 1: Champion Scenarios 

We are mainly going to be reviewing the generated code. We will also be reviewing the grow up story, with a specific example of Metrics Advisor. The issue will be updated with more specific scenarios closer to the release date.


## Thank you!

parameter will be of type `JSONObject`, and if they choose to generate with models (only msrest), the model input parameter will be the msrest model type, for example `models.Input`. What we want to do is if users generate with msrest models, we still want the operation to accept a `JSONObject` as an input parameter. This means this old operation:

```python
def my_operation(self, input: models.Input) -> None:
  _json = self._serialize.body(input, "Input")
```

Should look like this:

```python
def my_operation(self, input: Union[JSONType, models.Input]) -> None:
  serialize_type = "object" if isinstance(input, JSONType) else "Input"
  _json = self._serialize.body(input, serialize_type)
```
